result.execSummary:
The defendant Sharod Christopher Rimmer was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Robbery with Threat of Force [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(1)(b).
  • Carry Concealed Weapon, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.23(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: AS TO COUNTS 1 AND 3: Pay the DNA surcharge, costs and disbursements. Court ordered monies taken by the DOC's from up to 25% of prison funds. Balance would be then paid while on ES. If not paid by end of probationary period, balance converts to a civil judgment.

superMiscConds.notes:
CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
- No controlled substances or alcohol; Absolute Sobriety.
- AODA assessment; treatment, if needed.
- Urine screens to ensure compliance.
- Seek/maintain full time employment.
- No Contact with victim, Devron D., and co-actor, Jeremy Sims.

supervisions.notes: Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
